snippet.textDisplay:
We are completely missing the point. Two people involved in the fiasco are the partner and the celebrity. An incident took place in the celebrity's home. The partner gets hurt and the Police are called out to the incident. The partner is informed the incident has become a matter for enquiry where CPS were involved too and in the end the CPS has informed the celebrity that they will prosecute due to nature and seriousness of the injury inflicted by the celebrity in their home.

Since the death of the celebrity, blame has been aimed at the Police, CPS, social media, trolls, mental health and other excuses. However, if someone is ill, they do their utmost to get better. However, the blaming game has got to stop. This is about a woman who in the heat of the moment, hurt her partner. The Police were called but due to the seriousness the CPS were involved. It is sad she killed herself. However, social media, nor her management, nor the partner, nor the Police, nor CPS are to blame and nor is Love Island.

In the end of the day it is down to the actions of the celebrity which lead to consequences. The partner did not deserve to be hurt by her because Domestic Violence is very serious indeed and no one in this world has the right to inflict pain on another person.

Celebrities should not be exempt from prosecution in this matter neither.

Perhaps next time the names of the victim and the assailant should be kept out of the media until the trial is over and the verdict has been read out so no harm comes to either. Lessons can be learned from this.
